{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n`_do_reconverge` measures local-ahead by **HEAD**, not the branch ref\n(`src/rebar/_store/sync.py:95`, `rev-list {remote}..HEAD`; the ff-adopt `reset --hard {remote}`\nat `:97` runs only when that is empty). This is the WS3 data-loss fix: a tracker worktree can\nbe in a **detached-HEAD-local-ahead** state (a local commit advances `HEAD` but not\n`refs/heads/tickets`). The previous guard tested the lagging *branch ref*, read empty in that\nstate, and `reset --hard`'d away the un-pushed local commit (`docs/concurrency.md`). VALIDATED:\nthis specific edge has no dedicated regression test (the historical shell test was retired in\nthe bashâ†’Python migration without a like-for-like successor).\n\n## What\nAdd a regression test in `tests/unit/test_sync_union_recovery.py` that reproduces the\ndetached-HEAD-local-ahead state and asserts the local commit survives reconvergence:\n1. `origin` tickets repo with a shared **base** event; the tracker is cloned from it (so they\n   share history and `refs/heads/tickets` starts at base).\n2. `origin` advances with a new event (its `tickets` moves ahead of base).\n3. The tracker goes **detached** at base (`git checkout --detach`) and commits a LOCAL event â€”\n   so `HEAD` advances past base while `refs/heads/tickets` still points at base (lagging).\n4. `sync.reconverge(tracker)` runs (it fetches `origin`, then reconverges under the lock). With\n   the base as a common ancestor and both sides ahead, this is a DIVERGED case â†’ union merge.\n5. Assert the local event's commit is still reachable from `HEAD` (NOT orphaned by a\n   `reset --hard`), the remote event's commit is reachable too, and BOTH event dirs are present\n   in the working tree.\n\nTeeth: were local-ahead measured by the lagging `refs/heads/tickets` (the pre-WS3 bug) instead\nof `HEAD`, it would read empty, `reset --hard {remote}` would run, and the local commit would\nbe orphaned â€” failing the reachability assertion.\n\nSetup mechanics: `origin` is built with the file's existing `_new_tickets_repo` + `_commit_event`\nhelpers. The **tracker is created by `git clone -b tickets <origin>`** (NOT `_new_tickets_repo`,\nwhich only `git init`s an unrelated repo) so it shares the base history and starts with an\n`origin` remote + `origin/tickets` tracking ref; `_commit_event` and `_git` are reused for the\nsubsequent local commit and assertions. A small clone helper may be added if clearer.\n\n## Scope\n- `tests/unit/test_sync_union_recovery.py` â€” add the detached-HEAD-local-ahead test. Reuses\n  `_commit_event` / `_git`; builds `origin` via `_new_tickets_repo`; creates the tracker via\n  `git clone` (shared history) rather than `_new_tickets_repo`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A test `test_sync_preserves_detached_head_local_ahead_commit` reproduces the state (HEAD\n      detached and ahead; `refs/heads/tickets` lagging; `origin/tickets` advanced).\n- [ ] After `sync.reconverge`, both the local event commit and the remote event commit are\n      reachable from `HEAD`, and both event dirs exist in the working tree.\n- [ ] The local commit is not orphaned â€” it remains reachable (an aggressive `gc --prune=now`\n      would not collect it).\n- [ ] `make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783798821352486001,"uuid":"50c96972-5c7c-4985-8128-bf1f94a395c6"}